at one thing that everyone can agree upon is that they hope (or pray if they are religious) that those soldiers paraded on TV are ok. And i would suspect that pro and anti war people would also agree that those pictures are too much, too far, by the Iraqis.<br>
<br>
Where I suspect I will disagree with some of you is the hypocrisy and double standards surrounding the use of footage of POWs.<br>
These soldiers are professionals, and they are patriots. Their country has called upon them to do a job, and they are risking their lives to do it. Some may or may not agree with the policy aims of their leaders, but they are putting themselves in danger to carry out those aims. They run the risk of death in combat. But, there are some things they should not be exposed to. Primarily, they must be accorded the minimum accepted respect under the laws of war, under specifically the Geneva Conventions.<br>
Whilst i have been writing this paragraph, no doubt you will be agreeing and thinking of US/Uk servicemen. But it applies equally to Iraqis too.<br>
This is were the double standards come in. And i will list two specific examples.<br>
The day before the US POWs were put on public display, i was watching BBC news. I saw footage, with my own eyes of iraqi POWs. Close ups of their hands bound with those plastic handcuffs. A long line up of barefooted men. The caption on the footage said &quot;Ministry of Defence video&quot;. I thought to myself, this is a bit much.  I don't get to see much US TV, but i have read reports of iraqi POWs being &quot;interviewed&quot; on US TV. Perhaps you can fill in the details of this for me.<br>
The hypocrisy is apparent here. When Iraqi POWs are paraded on tv, no comment is passed. When US ones are paraded, it is a war crime. Why? What is the difference? They are all soldiers doing a tough job, both risking their lives for what they believe.  Does the US soldier have more rights than his iraqi counterpart? Do war crimes not count if either (a) it is your own side committing them, or (b) if you are the winner?<br>
<br>
Specific example 2 of hypocrisy. Taliban POWs in Camp X ray. Humiliation and degradation. Religious men shorn of their beards. A complete disregard for the Geneva Conventions. The argument, that geneva doesn't apply to these people.  We all saw the pictures of public humiliation of those particular prisoners. It seems gross hypocrisy to deride Iraq for breaching the laws of war when the US continues to breach those same rules of war in Guantanomo Bay. I note iraq using the same false arguments as the us in cuba &quot;these aren't pows. they are illegal combatants, however, we will give them geneva convention rights anyway&quot;<br>
<br>
Side note to varmarrz. Sorry, i got the name wrong, i don't have your name up here. you said, in connection with camp x ray <br>
&quot; I'm sure if they were innocent of any wrong doing they wouldn't be detained.&quot;  <br>
Your faith in your armed forces and military intelligence is admirable to the extent of being blind. Quite apart from the fact that this completely reverses the burden of proof and the presumption of innocence (two great aspects of the american legal system) and that is illogical, it is quite simply wrong. I remember watching a report about 3 months ago about a Pakistani who was released after a year from camp x ray when the authorities finally decided that he was innocent and had done nothing wrong. Your philosophy turns the fact of arrest into the proof of crime.<br>
<br>
Final point, if only there was some way to independently verify this things. Some judicial process separate from the two warring sides who can only be expected to support their own.<br>
But wait, there is, it is the international criminal court.<br>
It entered into force on the 1st of July 2002 and has 139 signatories and 89 parties. (meaning that 139 states signed up to it, but only 89 so far have ratified the treaty in their domestic law).<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://untreaty.un.org/ENGLISH/bible/englishinternetbible/partI/chapterXVIII/treaty10.asp#N6">untreaty.un.org/ENGLISH/b...y10.asp#N6</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
is where you can read up on the treaty.<br>
<br>
The Uk has ratified it, as has france and israel. russia has signed but not rafied. iraq has neither signed nor ratified. the US did sign up to it, but subsequently sent the following note:<br>
<br>
In a communication received on 6 May 2002, the Government of the United States of America informed the Secretary-General of the following:<br>
<br>
&quot;This is to inform you, in connection with the Rome Statute of the International Criminal Court adopted on July 17, 1998, that the United States does not intend to become a party to the treaty. Accordingly, the United States has no legal obligations arising from its signature on December 31, 2000. The United States requests that its intention not to become a party, as expressed in this letter, be reflected in the depositary's status lists relating to this treaty.&quot;<br>
<br>
Cries to international law would have alot more force if the US engaged with the rest of the world, or even obeyed it themselves.<br>
<br>
Of course, the ones doing the suffering on the ground are the ordinary soldiers, iraqi and american. the fact that their leaders choose to play fast and loose with truth and international law should not be an excuse to maltreat any pow be they american or iraqi.<br>
