<br>
Here's a great article written today by the political writer,  Visiting Fellow at Green College Oxford, and Guardian correspondent George Monbiot.  It describes the legal and political implications of actions taken by both countries as regards prisoners of war.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/Columnists/Column/0,5673,921411,00.html">www.guardian.co.uk/Column...11,00.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
It's worth noting that US governments in general have a poor overall record in terms of preserving the civil rights of detainees and PoWs.  In fact, one of the less famous findings of the Nuremberg proceedings was that Nazi commanders, particularly the Luftwaffe adhered far more closely to the rules of war regarding captured soldiers than their US, or even British counterparts.  The US was then condemned for its shabby treatment of civilian authorities arrested without charge after the occupation of Berlin and its aggressive interrment without charge of Japanese Americans.  Naturally the proceedings were overshadowed by far more pressing and brutal crimes of war- but let us not forget about them.<br>
<br>
Camp X-Ray simply signals to me, a continuation of American administrations sacrificing civil rights for a false sense of security.  The stateless limbo of &quot;unlawful combatants&quot; in Cuba (lacking all constitutional protection) created by the current US administration is not just in technical breach of the Geneva Convention- it is also under the ICC's provisions...a war crime.  <br>
<br>
Unsuprising then perhaps, as Monbiot says, that the Bush administration is entirely unwilling to place the instruments of this barbaric dehumanizing policy at risk of international prosecution.  Holding so many people without recourse to legal advice, without <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>any</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> basic right to be charged or held to account by judicial review is not the act of a democracy.  It is the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>very thing</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> we denounce dictators for- the circumvention of judicial process to serve a political end- and it's happening in what purports to be the freest of all nations, at least in principle.  <br>
<br>
The Bush administration talks of defending freedom- try telling that to the thousands of prisoners held without charge or trial- what freedoms do they enjoy?  Many of them are aid workers, teachers and local professionals- how is holding them without evidence or trial in any way defending freedom?  <br>
<br>
It's up to every one of us to ask these questions- if we fail to confront basic acts of evil at home, how can we have <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>any</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> credibility in confronting them overseas?  As many point out, we have the right to speak up against brutal and barbaric acts in a democracy.  But how are we any more empowered than the oppressed people of Iraq if we censor ourselves into silence, fearful that standing up for the freedom of the oppressed is unpatriotic just because they &quot;might be terrorists&quot;?  Everything I know about America and Americans before 9/11 tells me that they are a fair people, (often duped by cynical and callous politicans with the aid of a pliable media)- but basically a fair and humane people.  The question many abroad ask is this- how can you let your government get away with this basic betrayal of the fundamental principles that makes America great?<br>
<br>
9/11 was a tragedy, a terrible and brutal reminder of what we all face.  Americans have a choice- to trust a government, many of whom helped train terrorist elements that now threaten us all- to trust such people to do the right thing.  I have submitted before all of you in more than one thread that the majority of the current administration cares only about their short-term political survival, not for a lasting resolution.  Their short-sighted policies in the very recent past contain far more solid links to terrorism than Saddam Hussein ever did- terorrism that not only killed 3,000 innocents in New York, but still threatens the world.  <br>
<br>
  But the other, more sensible choice is to aggressively question the wisdom of policies that create terrorists- to mediate disputes, not take sides and trigger conflict.  History points the way, yet these men in power will not follow- violent problems can almost never ultimately have violent solutions in a modern and complex world.  Israel/Palestine, India/Pakistan, North/South Korea- all the world's existing flashpoints are sad continuous tales of violence begetting violence, suspicion and mistrust replacing the facts.  Cyprus, Northern Ireland, Sri Lanka- these are our models, where violence has been met not with more violence- but by a willingness to compromise for peace.  I fear very much that a large percentage of the American public is willing to give the men who armed bin Laden a blank cheque to flex their muscle as they choose- and that is the fear of many around the world.  But we can only fear and hope- it is up to the American people to make the right choice for them, and for the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>lasting</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> peace and stability of the international order- it's up to you.<br>
