Brilliant point- the fear now is that they will continue to be mistrustful of those coalition forces or lose collective confidence in the force's ability to keep them safe.  That is precisely why a UN mandate was so crucial- as long as the international community was seen to support it, in particular if Syria could have been persuaded to vote for the resolution or abstain- there would be far more chance of them taking us at our word when we say &quot;liberation not occupation&quot;.  The fact that the international community laughed the idea of hasty pre-emptive war out of the Security Council means that Iraqis will be a hundred times more suspicious of the motives of this conflict.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The situation in your part of the world would seem a bit easier to work out though. This is just speculation by me, but common bonds such as customs, language, and religion(albeit they are different, but they are still all Christians) would make an easier field to play on<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Not strictly speaking true- the issue isn't a religious one, but a sectarian one.  On the point of language/culture- Gaelige and English couldn't be more different tongues, and there are differences between cultural influences on political thought.  The gun had a powerful place in Irish politics for almost a century for example, some would argue that it still does for several paramilitary organizations.  And there aren't just two sides to the dispute, it's a multifaceted problem.  <br>
<br>
Unionists, Nationalists and Republicans are the broad divisions, but a myriad of political parties and interest groups are peppered with different views, political solutions and institutional reform.  Only recently, when the British government was prepared to compromise its long-standing principle of &quot;devolving power to terrorists&quot;- was a resolution on the table.  Fraught with difficulties I grant you- but far more acceptable than civilian loss of life and steady losses to the RUC and British security forces, bleeding them at a steady but no less attritional rate.  The Stormont Assembly is not a perfect organ of devolved government, but it is far more palatable than British soldiers returning in body bags year upon year and fringe groups like the RIRA/ULPG perpetrating terrorist acts on the British and Irish mainlands.  The Omagh bomb was a stark wake-up call to the realities and choices staring us in the face.  History will not say that we blinked first- rather that we took the brave political step of laying a stiff and belligerent government doctrine on the altar of peace.  <br>
<br>
The Israel-Palestine problem on paper is a lot easier to resolve.  Far from having to assemble a myriad of political parties and interest groups into a devolved government, you are dealing with two sides, a far more classical diplomatic dispute.  One of these sides is an elected representative government- so dealing with them is simple in practical terms <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>assuming they wish to sue for peace</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  The same obviously applies on the Palestinian side.  At present, neither side seems interested in compromising entrenched political views in favour of peace.  Sharon for selfish political reasons is happy to exploit violence to cement his position.  The Palestinian Authority has made some reforms- the formation of the Prime Minister's cabinet will tell us if these are a genuine drive for change, or merely a token effort.  <br>
<br>
I strongly suspect that latter- hardline elements will be foricbly bullied out of the future cabinet of Palestine- creating resentment and popular opposition.  We need all concerns represented fairly and democratically- until that happens there is no reason the many on the Israeli side feel they need to deal with the PA.  And on the other side of the coin- many in the PA see it futile to negotiate with Israel whilst under occupation- they are demanding a neutral platform.  It is hard to sound credible as a Palestinian negotiater if the future national infrastructure you're banking on to help form a nation-state is daily ripped to shreds by the Israeli army.  On the other hand, Palestinian terrorism only serves to strengthen the Israeli negotiating position- Sharon knows this and is so unwilling to make the sacrifices needed for peace.  <br>
<br>
Yes there are difficulties- I suspect Sharon and Arafat will both have to go before serious negotiation has any chance of success.  And let's not kid ourselves- such negotiation is crucial to the peace of the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>entire region</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  Look at the text of Saddam's speeches- his closing words are always &quot;Long live Iraq, long live Palestine&quot;.  The political exploitation allows Saddam and other dictators in the region (mostly US/UK allies or surrogates) to cement their position in power.  Without the rancid double-standards- offering half a billion dollars of aid to starving Iraqis while giving 1 billion to Israel (plus 9 billion in loan write-offs) is just one example of this.<br>
<br>
Without a fair and even hand in the region we can never hope to achieve peace.  If that fair and even hand is used (and every indication is that the Bush administration isn't interested in dealing even-handedly)- if it is used, then there is genuine hope for leadershp change on both sides and a realistic path to peace.  The final solution is universally agreed upon in principle- Resolution 230 will <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>finally</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> be implemented, creating a viable Palestinian state based on pre-1967 borders.  Israel will be recognized fully by this state, border work will be shared and indeed citizenship will be shared until organs of government are constructed.  <br>
<br>
Our government will play a major role in that construction- but we too cannot be taken seriously until we cease our unconditional support for brutal suppressions of human rights undertaken by a democracy.  Camp X-Ray brought it home to all of us that democracies under threat can be just as savage and uncaring as the vilest regimes on the planet.  The fact that Israel is a democracy does not excuse its forces from the gross human rights abuses it perpetrates.  Indeed it is even more important that democratic forces are held accountable.<br>
<br>
That is a reasonably detailed preamble to any peace deal- and for all our sakes- I hope it would deal a lethal blow to the spectres of both the brutal state repression of Israel, and more importantly to terrorism which threatens us all.  These are difficult and unstable times weighing upon us, we have set aside this crucial goal in favour of creating additional instability elsewhere.  If we truly want peace in the region and on our doorstep- this would be firmly at the top of the priority list.  <br>
<br>
Sadly the Bush administration isn't big on vision beyond their immediate objectives- and that has the potential to harm us all.  As long as terrorists leaders can link their struggle with the Palestinian freedom struggle- their recruitment targets will certainly always be met.  We need to engage with the mind of a would-be terrorist- resolution of this conflict would settle a lot of grievances for a lot of people.  If that chance presents itself to us- we and the parties concerned have a sacred duty to grab it with both hands. <p>Taranna Dhossarim<br>
